<p class="deviceParagraph" align="left" style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">
Our analysis of the Summer Budget seeks to provide insight and opinion into what Government policy means for our industry, rather than being a simple reiteration of the key measures.
</p><p class="deviceParagraph" align="left" style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">
We found that, although this Budget laid claim to being bold and to putting 'security' first, closer study suggests it may be remembered more for social engineering, and a step in closing the productivity gap, than for fiscal engineering 

and new infrastructure. 
</p><p class="deviceParagraph" align="left" style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">
Key issues in and around this Budget include:
</p>
<ul class="deviceParagraph" align="left" style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">
<li>competitive tax measures, such as on VAT and corporation tax, intended to reinforce internationally that the UK is leading the way for global business</li>
<li>a future Roads Fund, but with a significant gap in interim highways funding </li>
<li>a potential reduction in publically funded housing of 4,000 units per year</li>
<li>a statement of intent that at least part of the onus of solving and financing the productivity puzzle will be placed firmly on UK business</li>
<li>a welcome re-prioritisation of Network Rail but no mention of major rail schemes </li>
</ul>
<p class="deviceParagraph" align="left" style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">
Despite a big build up, given it is the first truly Conservative Budget in nearly two decades, for our industry too much has been deferred: capital spending, addressing productivity, fiscal reform and planning.  We now look forward to 

what has been billed as a 'rigorous' Spending Review.
</p><p class="deviceParagraph" align="left" style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">
<a style="color:#578429" href="http://www.360ingenuity.com/aecom/emails/AECOM%20Summer%20Budget%202015%20Commentary.pdf"><span style="color:#578429"><b>Download our full response to the Summer Budget 2015</b></span></a>
</p>
